<section xml:id="s_modules" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title><m>R</m>-modules</title>

    <definition xml:id="d_module">
    <title><m>R</m>-module</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a ring. A <term>(left) <m>R</m>-module</term> is a triple <m>(M,+,\cdot)</m>, where <m>(M,+)</m> is an abelian group and <m>\cdot</m> is a function 
    <md>
        <mrow>\cdot R\times  M \amp \rightarrow M </mrow>
        <mrow>(r,m) \amp \mapsto rm</mrow>
    </md>
    satisfying the following axioms.
    <ol marker="(i)">
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>(r+s)m=rm+sm</m> for all <m>r,s\in R</m> and <m>m\in M</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>r(m+n)=rm+rn</m> for all <m>r\in R</m> and <m>m,n\in M</m>
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>(rs)m=r(sm)</m> for all <m>r,s\in R</m> and <m>m\in M</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>1m=m</m> for all <m>m\in M</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    We call the operations <m>M\times M\xrightarrow{+}M</m> and <m>R\times M\xrightarrow{\cdot} M</m> <term>module addition</term> and <term>scalar multiplication by <m>R</m></term>, respectively. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <example xml:id="eg_modules_R">
    <title>Ring objects as modules</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a ring.
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>R</m> is itself an <m>R</m>-module, where module addition is ring addition, and scalar multiplication is ring multiplication. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                If <m>I</m> is a left ideal of <m>R</m>, then <m>I</m> is a left <m>R</m>-module, where module addition is ring addition, and scalar multiplication is (left) multiplication by elements of <m>R</m>. Note that this scalar multiplication is well-defined precisely because <m>I</m> is closed under multiplication on the left by arbitrary elements of <m>R</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Let <m>I</m> be a left ideal of <m>R</m>. The quotient group <m>R/I</m> is an <m>R</m>-module, where module addition is the usual coset addition and scalar multiplication is defined as 
                <md>
                    <mrow>r\cdot (s+I) \amp =rs+I</mrow>
                </md>
                for all <m>r\in R</m> and <m>s+I\in R/I</m>. Once again, the fact that this operation is well-defined is a result of <m>I</m> being closed under multiplication on the left by elements of <m>R</m>. Indeed, assume <m>s+I=s'+I</m>, so that <m>s'=s+I</m>. We then have 
                <md>
                    <mrow>rs'\amp = r(s+i) </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = rs+ri</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = rs+i'</mrow>
                </md>
                for some <m>i'\in I</m>, showing that <m>rs+I=rs'+I</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                If <m>R</m> and <m>S</m> are rings and <m>\phi\colon R\rightarrow S</m>, then <m>S</m> has the structure of an <m>R</m>-module. Module addition is just ring addition in <m>S</m>, and scalar multiplication by elements of <m>R</m> is defined as follows: 
                <md>
                    <mrow>R\times S \amp \rightarrow S</mrow>
                    <mrow>(r,s) \amp \mapsto \phi(r)s</mrow>
                </md>.
                That this satisfies the scalar multiplication axioms follows in a straightforward manner from (a) the fact that <m>\phi</m> is a ring homomorphism, (b) the fact that <m>R</m> is a ring, and (c) the fact that <m>S</m> is a ring. You are invited to verify this yourself. 
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="eg_module_field">
    <title>Modules over fields</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>F</m> be a field. An <m>F</m>-module <m>M</m> is the same thing as a vector space over <m>F</m>. Indeed, modules should be considered as a straightforward generalization of a vector space, where the base field of the vector space is replaced with an arbitrary ring.  
    </p>
    </statement>
    
    </example>
    <example xml:id="eg_module_Z">
    <title>Modules over <m>\Z</m></title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    A <m>\Z</m>-module is the same thing as an abelian group. Indeed, if <m>M</m> is a <m>\Z</m>-module, then in particular <m>M</m> is a an abelian group with respect to its module addition. Conversely, given an abelian group <m>(G,+)</m>, it is easy to see (using an induction argument) that the operation
    <md>
        <mrow>\Z\times G\amp\rightarrow G </mrow>
        <mrow>(n,g) \amp \mapsto ng </mrow>
    </md>
    is the unique scalar multiplication by <m>\Z</m> that can be defined on <m>G</m>. Recall that for an abelian group <m>(G,+)</m>, given <m>n\in \Z</m> and <m>g\in G</m>, we define <m>ng</m> is defined to be the <m>n</m>-fold addition of <m>g</m> with itself if <m>n</m> is positive, the <m>\abs{n}</m>-fold addition of <m>-g</m> with itself if <m>n</m> is negative, and <m>0_G</m> if <m>n=0</m>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </example>
    <definition xml:id="d_submodule">
   <title>Submodule</title>
   <statement>
   <p>
   Let <m>M</m> be an <m>R</m>-module. A <term>submodule</term> of <m>M</m> is a subset <m>N\subseteq M</m> satisfying the following properties. 
   <ol marker="(i)">
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>N</m> is a subgroup of <m>(M,+)</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>N</m> is closed under scalar multiplication: <ie/>, if <m>r\in R</m> and <m>m\in N</m>, then <m>rm\in N</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
   </ol>
   </p>
   </statement>
   </definition>
   <definition xml:id="d_module_homo">
   <title>Module homomorphism</title>
   <notation>
    <usage><m>\Hom_R(M,N)</m></usage>
     <description>set of <m>R</m>-module homomorphisms from <m>M</m> to <m>N</m></description>
   </notation>
   <notation>
    <usage><m>\End_R(M)</m></usage>
     <description>set of <m>R</m>-module endomorphisms of <m>M</m></description>
   </notation>
   <statement>
   <p>
Let <m>R</m> be a ring. An <term><m>R</m>-module homormorphism</term> between two <m>R</m>-modules <m>M</m> and <m>N</m> is a group homomorphism <m>\phi\colon M\rightarrow N
   </m>, satisfying <m>\phi(rm)=r\phi(m)</m> for all <m>r\in R</m>. 
</p>
<p>
    The set of all <m>R</m>-module homomorphisms from <m>M</m> to <m>N</m> is denoted <m>\Hom_R(M,N)</m>. An <m>R</m>-module homomorphism from <m>M</m> to itself is called an <term><m>R</m>-module endomorphism</term>. We write <m>\End_R(M)=\Hom_R(M,M)</m>: <ie/>, <m>\End_R(M)</m> is the set of all endormorphisms of <m>M</m>.
</p>
   </statement>
   </definition>
   <activity xml:id="spec_mod_homs">
   <title>Module structure of <m>\Hom_R(M,N)</m></title>
   <statement>
   <p>
   Let <m>M</m> and <m>N</m> be <m>R</m>-modules. Given <m>\phi,\psi\in \Hom_R(M,N)</m> and <m>r\in R</m>, we define <m>R</m>-module homomorphisms <m>\phi+\psi</m> and <m>r\phi</m> as follows:
   <md number="yes">
    <mrow>(\phi+\psi)(m) \amp = \phi(m)+\psi(m)</mrow>
    <mrow>(r\phi)(m) \amp =r\phi(m)</mrow>
   </md>.
   The operations 
   <md>
    <mrow>\Hom_R(M,N)\times \Hom_R(M,N) \amp \rightarrow \Hom_R(M,N) \amp R\times \Hom_R(M,N)\amp \rightarrow \Hom_R(M,N)</mrow>
    <mrow>(\phi,\psi) \amp \mapsto \phi+\psi \amp (r,\phi)\amp \mapsto r\phi</mrow>
   </md>
   give <m>\Hom_R(M,N)</m> the structure of an <m>R</m>-module. 
   </p>
   <p>
    Additionally, <m>\End_R(M)</m> is a ring with respect to addition and composition, and the map <m>\phi\colon R\rightarrow \End_R(M)</m> is a ring homomorphism. If <m>R</m> is commutative, the homomorphism <m>\phi</m> gives <m>\End_R(M)</m> the structure of an <m>R</m>-algebra. 
   </p>
   </statement>
   </activity>
   <proposition xml:id="prop_mod_constructions">
    <title>Submodule constructions</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>M</m> and <m>N</m> be <m>R</m>-modules. 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        If <m>M_1</m> and <m>M_2</m> are submodules of <m>M</m>, then <m>M_1+M_2</m> is a submodule of <m>M</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        If <m>(M_i)_{i\in I}</m> is a family of submodules of <m>M</m> indexed by the nonempty set <m>I</m>, then <m>\bigcap_{i\in I}M_i</m> is a submodule of <m>M</m>.  
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Let <m>\phi\in \Hom_R(M,N)</m>.
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\ker\phi</m> is a submodule of <m>M</m>. 
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    If <m>N'</m> is a submodule of <m>N</m>, then <m>\phi^{-1}(N')</m> is a submodule of <m>M</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    If <m>M'</m> is a submodule of <m>M</m>, then <m>\phi(M')</m> is submodule of <m>N</m>. 
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Given a subset <m>A</m> of <m>M</m>, let <m>\mathcal{M}=\{M'\subseteq M\mid M' \text{ a submodule containing} A\}</m>, and define <m>(A)=\bigcap_{M'\in \mathcal{M}}M'</m>, the intersection of all submodules of <m>M</m> containing <m>A</m>.
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>(A)</m> is the smallest submodule of <m>M</m> (with respect to inclusion) containing <m>A</m>. 
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    If <m>A=\emptyset</m>, then <m>(A)=\{0\}</m>. Otherwise,
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow>(A) \amp =\left\{\sum_{i=1}^{n}r_im_i\mid n\in \Z_{&gt; 0}, r_i\in R, m_i\in A\right\} </mrow>
                                    </md>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Given <m>\phi\in \Hom_R(M,N)</m>, we have 
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow>\phi((A)) \amp = (\phi(A))</mrow>
                                    </md>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Proof by delegation.
        </p>
    </proof>
   </proposition>
   <definition xml:id="d_Rlinear_combo">
   <title><m>R</m>-linear combination</title>
   <statement>
   <p>
   Let <m>M</m> be an <m>R</m> module, and let <m>A</m> a subset of <m>M</m>. An <term><m>R</m>-linear combination</term> of the elements of <m>A</m> is an element of <m>M</m> of the form <m>\sum_{i=1}^{n}r_im_i</m>, where <m>n</m> is a positive integer, <m>m_1,m_2,\dots, m_n\in A</m>, and <m>r_1,r_2,\dots, r_n\in R</m>.
   </p>
   </statement>
   </definition>
   
   <definition xml:id="d_submodule_generated">
   <title>Generated submodule</title>
   <statement>
   <p>
   Given an <m>R</m>-module <m>M</m> and a subset <m>A\subseteq M</m>, the set <m>(A)</m> defined as the intersection of all submodules of <m>M</m> containing <m>A</m> is called the <term>submodule of <m>M</m> generated by <m>A</m></term>.
   </p>
   </statement>
   </definition>
   <remark>
    <title>Generated submodules and span</title>
    <p>
        The concrete description of <m>(A)</m> as the set of <m>R</m>-linear combinations of elements of <m>A</m> is the <m>R</m>-module analogue of the <em>span</em> of a collection of vectors. Later we will see an analogue of the the notion of linear independence. 
    </p>
   </remark>
   
   <activity xml:id="spec_module_quotient">
   <title>Module quotients</title>
   <statement>
   <p>
   Let <m>N</m> be a submodule of the <m>R</m>-module <m>M</m>. We define a scalar multiplication on the quotient group <m>M/N</m> as follows: given <m>r\in R</m>, <m>m+I\in M/N</m>, <m>r(M+N)=rm+N</m>. This is a well-defined operation, and <m>M/N</m>, together with coset addition and this scalar multiplication, is an <m>R</m>-module called the <term>quotient module</term> of <m>M</m> by <m>N</m>.  
   </p>
   </statement>
   </activity>
   <theorem xml:id="th_module_isom_ths">
   <title>The isomorphism theorems for modules</title>
   <statement>
   <p>
   Let <m>M</m> and <m>N</m> be <m>R</m>-modules. 
   <ol marker="(0)">
    <li>
        <p>
            Let <m>M'</m> be a submodule of the <m>R</m>-module <m>M</m>, and let <m>\pi\colon M\rightarrow M/M'</m> be the quotient map. Given any <m>\phi\in \Hom_R(M,N)</m> satisfying <m>M'\subseteq \ker \phi</m>, there is a unique <m>\overline{\phi}\in \Hom_R(M/M', N)</m> satisfying <m>\overline{\phi}=\overline{\phi}\circ \pi</m>: namely, the map <m>\overline{\phi}\colon M/M'\rightarrow N</m> defined as <m>\overline{\phi}(m+M')=\phi(m)</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            If <m>\phi\colon M\rightarrow N</m> is an <m>R</m>-module homomorphism, then <m>M/\ker\phi\cong \im \phi</m> as <m>R</m>-modules, and the map <m>\overline{\phi}\colon M/\ker\phi\rightarrow \im N</m> defined as <m>\overline{\phi}(m+\ker\phi)=\phi(m)</m> is an isomorphism. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
           If <m>M_1</m> and <m>M_2</m> are submodules of <m>M</m>, then <m>(M_1+M_2)/M_2\cong M_1/M_1\cap M_2</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Let <m>\phi\colon M\rightarrow N</m> be a surjective <m>R</m>-module homomorphism. If <m>M'</m> is a submodule of <m>M</m> containing <m>\ker\phi</m>, then 
            <md>
                <mrow> \amp N/\phi(M')\cong M/M'</mrow>
            </md>.
            In the special case where <m>M'</m> is a submodule of <m>M</m> and <m>\pi\colon M\rightarrow M/M'</m> is a quotient map, we write <m>\pi(M'')=M''/M'</m> for any submodule <m>M''</m> of <m>M</m>. Thus, in this case, if <m>M''</m> is a submodule of <m>M</m> containing <m>M'</m>, the isomorphism above is written
            <md>
                <mrow>(M/M')/(M''/M') \amp \cong M/M'' </mrow>
            </md>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Let <m>\phi\colon M\rightarrow N</m> be a surjective <m>R</m>-module homomorphism. The map 
            <md>
                <mrow> M' \amp \mapsto \phi(M')</mrow>
            </md>
            defines a bijection between set of submodules of <m>M</m> containing <m>\ker\phi</m> and the set of a submodules of <m>N</m>, with inverse given by the map
            <md>
                <mrow>N' \amp \mapsto \phi^{-1}(N')</mrow>
            </md>.
            Moreover this bijection preserves inclusions, intersections, sums, and quotients of submodules. 
        </p>
    </li>
   </ol>
   </p>
   </statement>
   <proof>
   <p>
   </p>
   </proof>
   </theorem>
   
   
    
    
    

